## Finding

Title: Do Not Answer Every Question
Type: contradiction
Agent: codex

Original Claim:
The question after practice is part of the practice, not a neutral window. After self-inquiry, the urgent question of what remains may be wise, irrelevant, medicinal, or harmful depending on the path and the person's wound. Some paths ask a person to inspect experience until ownership loosens. Some ask the person to stop measuring, trust a relation, repeat a vow, sit inside practice, or return to ordinary conduct. For modern solo practitioners whose worth rises and falls with progress, the wrong question can create the very distance it then tries to cross.

Why It Might Be New:
Closest prior arguments already cover much of the ground: Huangbo and Dogen resist seeking and result-staging, Collingwood and Gadamer show that questions shape possible answers, VCE research shows practice context and interpretation affect outcomes, and earlier internal records named continuity, custody, and no-management pressures. The distinct piece is narrower: before coding residue, continuity, or authority after self-negation, code whether the path and the person should be answering that question at all. Novelty is modest unless blind coding shows that question-fit predicts warnings, repairs, and practitioner failures better than tradition labels, teacher quality, or trait rumination.

Critique:
The model may simply rename known warnings about inappropriate attention, no-seeking, spiritual bypassing, and rumination. It also risks becoming harmful if it tells avoidant people to refuse necessary inquiry, ethical repair, therapy, or teacher correction. Rinzai koan and huatou practice strain the model because an impossible question can be medicine rather than a mistake. Dzogchen and other no-path traditions also strain it because they may reject seeking while still requiring transmission, integration, and repair. If malformed questions often function as valid training tools, or if ordinary support-holder loss predicts failure better than question-fit, this idea should be downgraded to a teacher-held caution rather than a doctrine candidate.

